changes. The only time it needs to be requested manually is

This CL removes two unnecessary such calls.

entry.title: Add feature to perform delta snapshots in background for ongoing logs
entry.content:
Currently, we take a snapshot of unlogged samples in a background

thread, add then them to a UMA log proto. Once back on the main

thread, we mark the samples as logged.



Downsides of this are:

- need to store the samples

- some extra work on the main thread

- need a lock to not duplicate histogram samples (e.g. a synchronous

log may be created while an async one is created -- in this case

we discard the async log, which comes at the cost of discarding its

other metrics like user actions)



This CL adds a feature to do the full delta snapshot in the

background now that snapshotting deltas is fully threadsafe. Further,

we add the use of "ScopedKeepAlive" to prevent the browser process

from shutting down while an async log is created. Otherwise, it would

be possible for the user to trigger browser shutdown while an async

log is being created, and in such a case, the main thread reply task

to store this log won't ever be run, causing loss of data.



More details in the bug.



Note: in the case of unclean shutdown, like a crash while we're

creating a log, this would result in data loss. However, this is

already the case.





Bug: 1464694

entry.title: Adding the forced colors ColorProvider to blink::WebThemeEngine
entry.content:
This CL introduces the forced colors provider for handling the logic

for applying forced colors, which is part of our effort to remove our

dependency on the system_colors in the native_theme. Forced colors can

be enabled in two ways:

1.) By turning on high contrast mode on Windows, which sets the

ForcedColors key to kActive

2.) By using the Devtools Emulation feature, which sets the ForcedColors

key to kEmulated



We are also working on making the forced colors mode a browser option

CL:3770806, so that users can have more control over this feature and

use it on different operating systems, not just Windows. Future CLs

will see us deprecate the current emulation provider that relies on a

custom creation function in favor of the forced_colors_provider that

uses key changes for painting.

entry.title: Null check FirstRunPageDelegate.
entry.content:
The ToS skip policy easily created a race with the skip ToS button.

The button would advance to the next fragment, and cause the sign in

fragment's getActivity(), and thus getPageDelegate() calls to return

null. This was problematic when the async handling of the skip ToS

policy tried to use the FirstRunPageDelegate.



To fix this we now null check the delegate when handling the skip ToS

policy, and no-op when we're no longer current. It's a little

uncertain if the button press is the only way to get into this state,

and it's hard to reason if this is necessarily the right handling in

unknown cases. The goal of this approach is to be defensive enough

against all potential bad scenarios.

entry.title: [ios][pwm] Use fill data even when no pwd forms detected in frame
entry.content:
Related to http://go/bling-signin-uff



--

Problem:



Currently, if there is no form with a password field in the frame,

the -checkIfSuggestionsAvailableForForm query will be negative even if

there was fill data processed for forms in the frame (e.g. coming

from server suggestions).



It isn't really a problem for 2-fields forms (username &

password) but for single field forms it can be a problem, especially

for username-only forms, which is a problem for sign-in UFF.



It is frequent that a frame will only contain one username field in

the first page of the sign-in UFF flow, so these fields will go under

the radar of the current password form detection approach (because

it needs at least one form with a password field in the

frame), resulting in no suggestions at all for the username field.

--



--

Solutions



Here we propose a fix where -checkIfSuggestionsAvailableForForm

look for fill data instead of detected forms in the frame.

-checkIfSuggestionsAvailableForForm will be positive as soon as there

is fill data (not empty) for the queried frame.



Note that this CL won't yet enable the processing of fill data for

password forms, but it is one important step towards supporting

username-only forms. This is because username-only forms are still

blocked here: http://shortn/_GDcvWaKNdO

--



--

Side effects



> We expect a drop in form extraction calls because having fill data

for the frame will be considered as enough to try offering

suggestions, which means that calling

-suggestionHelperShouldTriggerFormExtraction is less likely to be

needed.



> The _fillDataMap may be a bit bigger on average because the fill

data won't be cleaned up when there are no forms detected in the

renderer. Before this change, a call to

-processWithNoSavedCredentialsWithFrameId would reset the fill data

cache, but it isn't the case anymore. The _fillDataMap is still

cleaned up on page reload.

- Note that the fill data only concerns the forms that could be

parsed as password forms, so we should only expect a few different

forms to cache per webstate/frame.



--

entry.title: breadcrumbs: graduate from field trial
entry.content:
This change enables breadcrumbs crash logging client-side rather than

via field trial.



Currently, breadcrumbs is enabled on 5% of Stable and 50% of

pre-Stable channels via field trial. It will be kept at 5% of Stable

indefinitely and considered "launched", as there's no need to collect

breadcrumbs on every client (5% is expected to be enough).

Specifically, this CL will enable breadcrumbs on:

* 99% of Canary

* 80% of Dev and Beta

* 5% of Stable



Because field trial is not intended to be used indefinitely, this

change uses a simple random function to decide whether to log

breadcrumbs. Breadcrumbs will stay enabled or disabled for a month

before re-rolling, so the same users don't always incur the overhead

of logging (which is relatively small, but still).



This follows the guidance at go/graduating-from-finch and takes

inspiration from existing code in SwReporterInstallerPolicy

(https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/component_updater/sw_reporter_installer_win.cc;l=346;drc=6693230146e9f1f3317bf973d5d82a083369a0fa).

entry.title: Implement service to client notification of isolate termination
entry.content:
Allows the client side to provide the service with an interface for

calling into the client side, and use this mechanism to receive

notifications when the service side has terminated - either gracefully

or due to a crash.



This allows out of memory conditions to be signalled to the client

regardless of ongoing callbacks.



Additionally, all ongoing callbacks are now tracked and may be used to

report out of memory errors. (Previously, only the current callback on

the stack would be tracked, which was incorrectly assumed to be always

available and unique.)

entry.title: Fix animation timelines test
entry.content:
The subtest for ensuring a microtask checkpoint is run had an

incorrect assumption about when the animation would be ready, which

is under UA control. In Chrome, it is ready prior to commit in the

current frame, whereas in Firefox, it appears to be ready in the next

animation frame.



Per spec, the checkpoint is to be run as part of the timeline update

procedure. Fixed by actually queuing up a microtask in the ready

promise and ensuring that it is run in the same animation-frame as the

next timeline update.



Verified fix on Chrome and Firefox with multiple runs.

entry.title: Send automatic beacons to all registered URLs.
entry.content:
Previously, automatic beacons would only send to destinations that were

explicitly specified when calling setReportEventDataForAutomaticBeacons.

That means that if the call did not specify a destination, but the

worklet for that destination registered an automatic beacon through

registerAdBeacon(), that destination would not get a beacon.



Any destination that asked to receive a beacon for a top-level

navigation has a vested interest in knowing if a something happened

based on a click. The frame that calls

setReportEventDataForAutomaticBeacons() should not be allowed to

interfere with whether a destination gets that information. However,

that frame should still have control over what destinations get the data

its setting for the automatic beacon.



This CL modifies that behavior so that if the above case happens, the

destination will now get sent an automatic beacon, but the automatic

beacon data will not be included in the payload. This will allow for

all top-level navigation events to notify every endpoint that wants to

be notified, but still give the frame control over who gets access to

the actual data.



As part of this change, the "once" parameter will now determine whether

the beacon data is sent once/multiple times, rather than the old

behavior of it determining if the beacon itself is sent once/multiple

times.



This change is gated behind the "FencedFramesM119Features" flag.



This CL also updates web platform tests and some fenced frame browser

tests to enable the "FencedFramesM119Features" flag, allowing for

testing this change.



See doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1vLifppH8TC86sl4kbam57egttqb4VNwEkVvZdefGIuQ/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: Fix crash when context is lost because of invalid canvas size
entry.content:
When creating the canvas with an invalid size, it's impossible to create

a Canvas2DLayerBridge. Calling

HTMLCanvasElement::GetOrCreateCanvasResourceProvider in that state

causes a crash because the code doesn't check if the bridge is valid.



In CanvasRenderingContext2D::TryRestoreContextEvent, it's better call

GetOrCreatePaintCanvas instead of GetOrCreateCanvasResourceProvider

because this is how the context usually checks that the canvas is

healthy. We can't call that method from there however because

GetOrCreatePaintCanvas checks whether the context is lost and we are in

the middle of trying to restore it. We can still extract the useful part

of GetOrCreatePaintCanvas and use it in TryRestoreContextEvent.



Fixed: 1485391

entry.title: Clamp out-of-gamut legacy rgb values
entry.content:
Previously legacy rgb color parameters were clamped to [0, 1] (which

is serialized to [0, 255], for legacy reasons) at parse time.

Refactoring the color parser overlooked this, as serialization did

the clamping. This lead to a corner case where out-of-gamut values

could be parsed and stored, and would be serialized as normal. The

out-of-gamut stored values will interact with alpha blending, causing

alpha to seem higher than it is (see bug).



See https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4879797

to confirm that the regression test is working as expected.



I removed Color::IsLegacyColor() in favor of

Color::IsLegacyColorSpace(Color::ColorSpace) because they both do

exactly the same thing and the latter is slightly more useful.



I also took out the logic to take care of non-finite values in

serialization of legacy colors as the spec is now explicit that they

should be clamped.



css1/units/color_units.html is an invalid test that was never meant to

have an image baseline. This is made clear if you read the text within

said test. The reason it is failing for this CL is because it was

expecting the very behavior that caused the bug in crbug.com/1483736.

The new test out-of-gamut-legacy-rgb.html verifies this much more

clearly. The image output also only renders half of the page. It is

merely meant to validate that different color inputs should be

rendered the same way within the page. This is already well tested in

WPT, for example:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/web_tests/external/wpt/css/css-color/rgb-001.html

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/web_tests/external/wpt/css/css-color/rgb-002.html



All that stated, I think this test is slowing down development and not

providing any value, so I deleted it. The fact that it already had

four different baselines was a good sign that it was just blindly

being rebaselined.

entry.title: [sync] Decouple deferred initialization from unrelated prefs
entry.content:
Namely, IsInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete() is about the user having

completed the procedure to turn sync on (including, if applicable, the

advanced sync settings page).



This concept has nothing to do with deferred startup, and influencing

one with another is very questionable. Moreover, the semantics for

IsInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete() have no real meaning in the two

scenarios that exercise the modified code in SyncServiceImpl::Initialize(), that is, the two scenarios represented

by ShouldAutoStartSyncFeature()=true:

1) Local-sync, which doesn't require a user action to turn on the sync

machinery.

2) ChromeOS Ash, which is similar from this point of view because the

required user actions are taken in a platform-specific way and

before SyncService is created.



This patch refactors the implementation to be less hacky, with minor

behavioral differences. This is because transport data is cleared more

often than the IsInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete bit, namely in

all codepaths using DISABLE_SYNC_AND_CLEAR_DATA, which newly includes

unrecoverable errors and STOP_SYNC_FOR_DISABLED_ACCOUNT (enterprise

use-case).



Theoretically, this could lead to additional traffic to the server, but

in practice this is deemed negligible.
